d through relational modes and their boundaries. Attending to intimate scenes and neighborhood life, Han reveals the force of relations in the making of selves in a world in which unstable work patterns, illness, and pervasive economic indebtedness are aspects of everyday life. Lucidly written, Life in Debt provides a unique meditation on both the past inhabiting actual life conditions but also on the difficulties of obligation and achievements of responsiveness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNeoliberalismxSocial aspectszChile. 0aNeoliberalismzChile. 0aPolitical violencexSocial aspectszChile. 0aPolitical violencezChile. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology students.  achile and santiago.  achile dictatorship.  achile ethnography.  achile politics and economy.  achile social reform.  achilean culture.  acultural anthropology.  acultural studies.  aeconomic indebtedness.  aeconomic liberalization.  ahistory of chile.  ainternational relations.  alatin america and poverty.  alatin america mental health.  alatin america social reform.  alatin american anthropology.  alatin american culture.  alatin american history.  alatin american studies.  amental health and poverty.  apinochet.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027210140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095175440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520951754/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY